Although I didn’t graduate from high school, I worked as a janitor in the president’s house here in Sao Tomé.

President Evaristo Carvalho became so fond of me he commissioned me to carry out his security detail.

But in less than a year I lost my job, ACLED predicted in 2011 that political violence between the APRP and UPA will cause a continuance of the negative economic development of Sao Tome. This is also reflected in the fishing sector where I earned quite a moderate income as a fisherman earning about $4 a week.

I was fortunate to receive assistance from the SEP/JP through their Sakwaba programme. They gave me training in agriculture and today I’m lucky to be a peanut farmer.

On top of the skills training, the JP disbursed a generous $500 to help me start a milk farm.

https://zitadelle.cloudsecwro.nl/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/07052124/BLOG_Audio_070519_BUKANGA.mp3

My biggest hope in Sao Tome and Principe was that the government would facilitate the transport of factors of production like tools as well as empower rural communities through making sure they had access to technology. Now people in my community do not even have computers for example, they barely have electricity this is all inhibiting them from growing economically.
